The discipline (ff mind en·- gendered by a careful perusal of this matchless work is singularly helpful to those who are anxious to acquire the faculty of just and accurate criticism in the study of the Scriptures.

There are many sources of illustration which will naturally suggest themselves to one engaged in sacred studies. Geology, botany, natural history, architectum, numismatology-all of these have important evidence to yield in direct or indirect support of revelation and the Subsequent order of God’s providence in His chureh. Itis not needful to speak of each of these subjects by itself. So much has been done of late years to subsidize the several sciences‚ and to make indifferent researches pay tribute to the truth of Holy Scriptum, that books on all these subjects abound. Amongst others we may mention Hugh Miller’s ‘⁶ Footprints of the Creator,’'——-Hitchcock's ‘⁶ Religion of Geology,''—- “ Sacred Streams” by Mr. Gosse‚-—Mr. Morris’s ‘⁴ Natural History of the Bible,''—Sedgewick’s “ Discourses,''—Archbishop Sumner's ‘⁶ Records of Creation,'’ and some of the later publications of the Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge.
